content.problemStatement:
We'll focus on defining and overriding multiple blocks in base templates.

First, let's create a base template (e.g., base.html) that includes the common structure of our web pages:

```html




    {% block title %}My Flask App{% endblock %}



        {% block header %}
        Welcome to My Flask App
        {% endblock %}



        {% block content %}
        {% endblock %}



        {% block footer %}
        &copy; 2023 My Flask App
        {% endblock %}



```

In this base template, we've defined several blocks using the {% block %} tag. These blocks act as placeholders that can be filled or overridden by child templates.

Now, let's create a child template (e.g., home.html) that extends the base template:

```html
{% extends "base.html" %}

{% block title %}Home Page{% endblock %}

{% block content %}
    Welcome to the Home Page
    This is the content of the home page.
{% endblock %}
```

In the child template, we use the {% extends %} tag to inherit from the base template. \
We then override specific blocks to customize the content for this particular page.

